  <h2>What the Distribution Box Does</h2>
  <p>
    After liquid leaves the tank, it arrives at the distribution box (or "D-box"), which sits between
    the tank and a drain field made up of several lines or trenches. The box's only job is to divide
    that flow evenly among the lines, so each one absorbs its fair share and no single section is
    overworked. A drain field is designed to last precisely because the load is spread across all of
    it. Even distribution isn't a detail — it's the whole principle the field depends on.
  </p>

  <h2>How It Goes Wrong</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Settling or shifting.</strong> Ground movement over time can tip the box out of level.
      Once it's tilted, gravity funnels too much flow to the lowest outlet and starves the higher
      ones — so one line is drowned while the others sit idle.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Clogging.</strong> Solids that shouldn't have reached the box, or invading roots, can
      block one or more outlets, again forcing uneven distribution.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The result.</strong> Part of the field is chronically overloaded and starts to fail at
      the surface, while the rest of the field never gets the chance to help.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why It Can Look Like Field Failure</h2>
  <p>
    Here's the reason this component deserves its own guide: an overloaded section of field produces
    exactly the signs of a failing field — wet ground, odors, slow drainage over one area. An owner
    (or an unlucky diagnosis) might conclude the whole field is done. But if the real culprit is the
    box sending everything to one line, the field itself may be fine, and the fix can be far more
    contained than a replacement. That gap — between "the field failed" and "the box needs
    attention" — is why an evaluation matters before committing to major work. Our guide on
    <a href="/signs-of-drain-field-trouble/">signs of drain-field trouble</a> covers the surface signs
    these problems share.
  </p>

  <h2>How It's Found and Addressed</h2>
  <p>
    Diagnosing a distribution-box problem means looking at the box itself and how flow is reaching each
    line — something an on-site evaluation is designed to do. Depending on what's found, addressing it
    may involve cleaning out a clog, re-leveling the box so flow divides evenly again, or repairing it.
    Often that's a more targeted job than working on the field as a whole. A provider determines what's
    appropriate for your system. To get it looked at, <a href="/request-service/">request septic
    service</a> and describe where you're seeing the wet or troubled area.
  </p>
